    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="193"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/14062</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Telegram Received by Mr. <persName type="from">Lauchlin
                            Currie</persName>, Administrative Assistant to President <persName
                            type="to">Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="63" xml:id="d193fn63">Copy received in the Department probably on July
                        3.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-02">July 2,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dr. Lauchlin Currie</hi>: Generalissimo just received
                    following reliable information: Japan has already decided in near future to
                    abrogate Soviet–Japan Neutrality Pact. Afterwards she will declare war on
                    Russia. Japan now is only hoping that in this affair America will maintain
                    neutral attitude in which case she would take immediate action to attack Russia.
                    Please inform President.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Segac</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <note n="63a" xml:id="d193fn63a">Probably the Naval Attaché for Air in China,
                        Maj. James M. McHugh, U. S. M. C.</note>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
